<dl id="s19006ao"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="us19" href="#s19006ao">Virtual: </a><a href="../../FF/unbs/s19all.htm#s19006ao">sector 6(ao)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> S. Scholastica</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="s19006ao"><li>Ulysses </li><li><a href="../../ulex/n/lexn.htm#s19006ao">2021</a> </li><li><a href="../../ulex/n/n86.htm#s19006ao">2017</a> </li><li><a href="../../ulex/n/n86.htm#s19006ao">1986 (12.1711)</a> </li><li><a href="../../ulex/n/l22n.htm#s19006ao">1922</a> </li><li><ms href="#s19006ao">MS NLI.10-27</ms> </li><li><a name="n1J1d" href="../udra/u12da.htm#n1J1d">Usage</a> </li><li><a href="../../ulex/n/n1J1d.htm#s19006ao">Draft: 12J.1</a></li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">S. BENEDICT <font color="green">[&hellip;]</font> Now S. Benedict had a sister, <mark>S. SCHOLASTICA</mark>, who had formed a society of nuns not far from her brother. He visited her once a year, and the last time, Scholastica, feeling that it was so, begged him not to depart; but as he persisted, a great storm came on in answer to her prayers, and he was obliged to remain longer with her. Three days after he saw her soul in the form of a dove flying to heaven. <small> E. A. Greene, <a name="EAGS" href="/udra/udex.htm#EAGS"><cite title="source">Saints and Their Symbols</cite></a> (1913), 48</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
